content:
Route to a Queue

Route work to queues to distribute the workload among a team of agents.

Available in: both Salesforce Classic and Lightning Experience
Omni-Channel is available in: Essentials, Professional, Enterprise, Performance, Unlimited, and Developer Editions
NOTE Implement this feature in one click with the Service Setup Assistant

Omni-Channel routes work through two separate processes.

First, when a new work item is assigned to an Omni-Channel queue, Omni-Channel attempts to route it to an agent. Omni-Channel routes work items by the priority of the queue that they’re assigned to, so the most important work items are pushed to agents first.

Next, items are routed based on how long they’ve been sitting in the queue. The oldest work items are pushed to agents before more recent ones.

Routing New Work Items

When a work item is created, it gets assigned to a queue. Omni-Channel determines which agents are available and how much work each agent is working on.

Routing Pending Work Items

When a new work item is added to the list of pending items, Omni-Channel determines whether it can immediately route the work item to an agent.

SCENARIO	WHAT HAPPENS
No agents are available. If there isn’t an agent online who has the right status, Omni-Channel keeps the work item in the list of items that need to be assigned to an agent.
Agents are available, but don’t have capacity for new work. If there are one or more agents who are available, Omni-Channel checks to see if any of those agents have the capacity to take on a new work item.
Agents are available and have capacity for more work. If there are agents that 1) are available and 2) have capacity to work on the item, Omni-Channel checks which agent to send the work to based on your organization’s routing settings.

When an Agent’s Ability to Receive Work Changes

When an agent logs in to Omni-Channel, finishes a work item, or changes status, Omni-Channel checks to see if there is any work that it can route to the agent.

SCENARIO	WHAT HAPPENS
The agent is away. Omni-Channel looks for another agent who can take the work.
The agent is available, but doesn’t have capacity for work. Omni-Channel looks for another agent who can take the work.
The agent is available and has capacity for more work Omni-Channel looks at the list of work items that are waiting to be routed to an agent.

Rerouting a Work Item

Sometimes an agent declines a work item or changes their presence status and are no longer available to accept work. In that case, the work item is rerouted until it finds a qualified agent.

Here’s what happens. First, Omni-Channel automatically changes the owner of the work item to the queue from which the object was originally routed. If an agent declines a work item, then Omni-Channel looks for another agent to route it to. However, the work item can be routed to the original agent again if the new agent declines it.

If an agent changes their status and is unavailable, then Omni-Channel looks for another agent to route the work to.

Omni-Channel repeats this process until the work item is routed to a qualified agent.

Assignment Rules, Auto-Response Rules, Escalation Rules, and Workflow Rules

Automation rules aren’t triggered when Omni-Channel routes a work item to an agent and the agent accepts the work.
title: Routing Work to Queues in Service Cloud
